    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-05-24T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-05-24T19:00:00-05:00" n="163"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">367n.1121 Hanovich, Israel/15: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Heizer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-05-24T20:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 24, 1924—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your May 21, 10 a.m. Pending recognition of British mandate over Palestine
                    protest should be made in any case where local courts assume jurisdiction over
                    American citizens. If further action taken against Hanovich in other than
                    Consular Court strong protest should be lodged and matter immediately reported
                    to Department.<note n="20" xml:id="d163fn20">The consul at Jerusalem reported in
                        despatch no. 211, July 15, 1924, that Hanovich had not been required to pay
                        the fine (file no. 367n. 1121 Hanovich, Israel/16).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
